# Native scrub / heavy-source playback вЂ” what NOT to do

This applies to the **native rebuild** under `app/` (Qt + MLT + WebEngine timeline).
It records failed approaches from real debugging on 3.4K 60fps footage (~3456Г—2234,
44 min and 7 min). Do not re-try these without new evidence.

## What actually works (keep this)

- **Backpressure scrubbing in the HTML UI** (`app/web/app.js`): at most **one seek
  in flight**; coalesce pointer moves to the latest cursor time; release the lock
  when a frame arrives (or on an adaptive safety timeout).
- **Adaptive safety timeout** derived from measured decode latency (`decodeEma`),
  always **above** real decode time. A fixed ~120 ms timer on heavy sources
  preempts in-flight decodes and re-creates the frozen-preview bug.
- **Consumer refresh path for scrubbing**: `seek в†’ purge в†’ refresh` on the paused
  transport; frames arrive via `consumer-frame-show`. Do not add a second render
  path unless you have proof it is faster *and* race-free.
- **1080p preview box** in the engine profile (scale down, never upscale source).
- **Proxy media** for editing when the source is huge вЂ” but only as **background /
  progressive** generation, never as a blocking вЂњwait 6+ minutes before editвЂќ gate.

---

## NEVER do these (ruled out with measurements)

### Scrub / seek UI

- вќЊ **Seek on every pointer move with no backpressure.** Pointer events arrive
  ~16 ms apart; decode takes ~35вЂ“250 ms on heavy sources. Each seekвЂ™s purge throws
  away the previous half-decoded frame в†’ preview **freezes while the playhead line
  moves**. This was the original backward-scrub bug.
- вќЊ **Fixed short safety timeout** (e.g. 120 ms) on heavy footage. When decode >
  timeout, the timer releases the lock mid-decode, the next seek purges, and you
  get ~4 seeks per 1 rendered frame. Use adaptive timeout from `decodeEma`.
- вќЊ **Move the playhead line from engine position echoes during scrub.** The
  cursor owns the line during drag; only playback should follow engine position.

### Engine / MLT consumer

- вќЊ **Stop the SDL audio consumer on every scrub gesture** (`consumer->stop()`).
  Measured **~800 ms per stop** (audio device teardown). This alone makes scrubbing
  feel unusable (вЂњplayhead wonвЂ™t catch the cursorвЂќ) even if decode is fast.
- вќЊ **Add a parallel вЂњdirect renderвЂќ scrub path** (`get_frame()` while the audio
  consumer still runs, or stop/start consumer around it) **without** proving no
  races and no double the latency. We tried this; it fought the working path and
  regressed UX.
- вќЊ **Seek to re-sync during playback.** Paused scrub uses purge+refresh; playback
  uses the audio consumer as master clock. Do not mix the two models.

### Keyframes / вЂњdynamic scrubвЂќ

- вќЊ **Assume keyframe-snapped seeking fixes 3.4K lag by itself.** Source already
  has ~1 s keyframe spacing. Snapping alone did not reduce engine latency; landing
  on an I-frame is not cheaper than decoding forward within a GOP on this stack.
- вќЊ **Build keyframe indexes with decode-based ffprobe** (`-skip_frame nokey` on
  frames). That decodes every keyframe and takes minutes. Use **packet flags only**
  if an index is ever needed again (~5 s for 44 min).
- вќЊ **Keyframe snap + direct render as the default scrub** without user-visible
  benefit. It added complexity and made scrubbing **worse** in the live app.

### Proxies / transcode

- вќЊ **Blocking full-file proxy at import** using `-hwaccel videotoolbox` on this
  source. Hardware decode was **~5Г— slower** than software for odd 3456Г—2234 H.264;
  full proxy landed ~2Г— realtime (~20 min for 44 min). Software decode + scale +
  hw encode в‰€ **6вЂ“7Г— realtime** (~6 min) вЂ” still too long to block the user.
- вќЊ **Parallel segment encodes expecting linear speedup.** Four concurrent jobs
  barely beat one (~7.6Г— vs ~6.7Г—) вЂ” encoder/memory bandwidth saturates.
- вќЊ **Proxy as the only plan** without background/progressive generation. CapCut
  feels instant because editing starts on the original and proxies swap in later.

### вЂњStructuralвЂќ misdiagnoses

- вќЊ **Treat RSS growth during wide seeks as a leak.** On 44 min 3.4K, ~1 GB RSS
  was live decode buffers across seek distance, not unbounded leak. MLT cache-bounding
  properties did not help.
- вќЊ **Split one long clip into many sequential clips** expecting less lag. Same
  source resolution and same per-seek decode cost; timeline length does not change
  per-frame work.
- вќЊ **Allocate more RAM to the app.** Does not reduce per-seek decode cost.
- вќЊ **Lower preview output resolution alone** expecting faster scrub. Measured:
  1080 в†’ 180 px preview profile did **not** change seek latency; cost is in producing
  a new source frame after seek, not in final scale.
- вќЊ **Use hardware decode in ffmpeg/MLT for this file without benchmarking.**
  Software decode was ~9Г— realtime vs VideoToolbox ~1.8Г— on the same sample.

